Jon Coonan6:09 PM

The process of the selection of our logo happened during the first year of the team, and since they we have stuck with the same choice of colors and imagery in the logo. The primary reason is called branding, essentially we want ALL our stuff to be the same so it is recognizable as ours, we have a designated font (SF Transrobotics), certain colors that we use (#1455fb blue and #fcff00 yellow). These were also chosen for a reason, the blue and yellow stand out in a sea of brightly colored team shirts at competition as well as match our school colors. The logo itself; what you see on our shirts and site as well as our flag, stickers, buttons, banner, biz cards, trailer (used to store the robot for travel) etc was designed by a marketing student in our teams first year.

While I applaud your friend for his/her creativity, we can’t use the logo because it does not fit within our branding guidlines, mostly due to the color, font, and style differences. Even if we could the rebranding cost of having to print new flags, buttons, stickers etc would be massive. Sorry

SO, the team needs to create and submit an Avatar to FIRST in time for the Avatar to be reviewed and approved. I would be glad to work with a student or two on this. Are any students interested in working on this?

Chris Rininger1:53 PM

While we're on the topic of possible sponsors & companies to engage, a while back a few of us were discussing the possibility of outsourcing some manufacturing (due to time crunch or if we needed a lot of a single part made or ?). It might even be that one or more of these business would sponsor us. The top candidate we found was Puget Sound Precision, a full service machine shop located in Poulsbo. http://www.pugetsoundprecision.com/>. This place looks amazing. Beyond that, there was another machine shop in Kingston, plus a few places that do sheet metal manufacturing (including https://www.morganmetalworks.com/> which does high-end installations at places like Starbucks).

I think it would take partnership between the marketing team and the mech/fabrication folks on the team to reach out to these kinds of businesses to try to develop relationships. It could be a very positive development for the team if it were accomplished. Many of the big elite teams are able to spend more time on design because they have sponsors who turn much of their manufacturing around very quickly. Something to think about.
